Date: Fri 25 Mar 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Arab Times (Kuwait) online, Reuters report, Fri 25 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://www.arabtimesonline.com/arabtimes/breakingnews/view.asp?msgID=8375>

Angola: Marburg Outbreak Toll Rises to 114
------------------------------------------
A total of 114 people in Angola, including an Italian doctor, have
died in an outbreak of the rare Marburg hemorrhagic fever, and health
officials said on Fri 25 Mar 2005 they feared that the deadly virus
could spread to Luanda.
2 people -- including the doctor who had been in direct contact with
Marburg patients -- had died in Luanda after coming to the capital
from northern Uige province to receive treatment, Filomeno Fortes,
department head for disease control at the health ministry told
Reuters.
A further 4 people in Luanda were also suspected of being infected
with Marburg hemorrhagic fever, but Fortes said all 6 cases in the
capital had come in from Uige. "Of the 6 cases we've had in Luanda,
we've had 2 deaths until now. All 6 came from Uige. None of these
represents a primary case from Luanda," Fortes said. "Our fear is
that if we don't control cases coming from Uige, there is a risk that
they could infect people in Luanda," he added.
The health ministry had sent mobile teams across Luanda to test
suspect cases and to check up on people who had been in contact with
identified cases, with hospital chiefs also putting in place
preparatory measures in case of a local outbreak. Health ministry
spokesman Carlos Alberto, speaking to Reuters by phone from Uige,
confirmed 112 people in the province about 225 km (140 miles) north
of Luanda had died from Marburg fever but said the death toll could
be even higher. "We've only registered cases dealt with in hospitals,
but it's possible people have also died in their homes without coming
to hospital," Alberto said.
With a health infrastructure shattered by decades of civil war,
Angola is facing a monumental challenge in trying to combat the
virus. The 1st case was detected late in 2004, and so far most of the
victims have been children. "We've already had some help from the
international community but more help would be welcome. We need
cleaning materials, medicines, protective clothing, that kind of
thing," Alberto said.
